      OpenSea insider trading
   =20
 =20
A famous fact of US securities law is that there is no law against insider =
trading. What there is is a law against securities fraud: It is illegal =E2=
=80=9Cto employ any device, scheme, or artifice to defraud=E2=80=9D someone=
 in connection with a securities trade.[1] For a long time courts have inte=
rpreted that to include insider trading, and there is a Securities and Exch=
ange Commission rule=C2=A0clarifying that in fact insider trading counts as=
 a scheme or artifice to defraud. But there is no law against insider tradi=
ng specifically; instead, insider trading is a=C2=A0type of fraud.It is a w=
eird type of fraud: If an executive of a public company trades on inside in=
formation about her company, she is defrauding shareholders, to whom she ha=
s a fiduciary duty. (This is called =E2=80=9Cclassical=E2=80=9D insider tra=
ding.) If the executive tells her therapist about an upcoming merger, and t=
he therapist trades on that knowledge, the therapist is betraying the execu=
tive, to whom he has a =E2=80=9Cduty of trust or confidence,=E2=80=9D and t=
hat betrayal=C2=A0plus=C2=A0the therapist=E2=80=99s trading also counts as =
fraud.=C2=A0(This is called =E2=80=9Cmisappropriation=E2=80=9D insider trad=
ing.) My shorthand is that =E2=80=9Cinsider trading is not about fairness, =
it=E2=80=99s about theft=E2=80=9D: If you have some duty to someone to keep=
=C2=A0nonpublic information secret, and you trade on that information, then=
 you have committed insider trading. You have committed securities fraud.No=
w, insider trading is a type of=C2=A0securities=C2=A0fraud. But there is an=
other federal statute that makes it a crime to use =E2=80=9Cany scheme or a=
rtifice to defraud=E2=80=9D someone using a phone or the internet.[2] This =
crime is generally called =E2=80=9Cwire fraud,=E2=80=9D and it is much broa=
der than securities fraud. Securities fraud is doing fraud about securities=
. Wire fraud is doing fraud about=C2=A0absolutely anything, as long as you =
do the fraud using email or the phone or text messages or a chat app, and i=
n 2022 you certainly do. So every fraud is wire fraud.You might put these t=
hings together and conclude: If insider trading in securities is securities=
 fraud, then insider trading in=C2=A0anything=C2=A0is wire fraud. If inside=
r trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0using information from someone else, to whom you h=
ave a duty to keep it confidential, to buy for your own account =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is a =E2=80=9Cdevice, scheme, or artifice to defraud=E2=80=9D under s=
ecurities law, then surely it is also a =E2=80=9Cscheme or artifice to defr=
aud=E2=80=9D under wire-fraud law. If you buy real estate based on insider =
knowledge of where Amazon.com Inc. is going to put its new headquarters, an=
d you had some duty to Amazon to keep that knowledge private, maybe that is=
 insider trading in real estate. If you make sports bets based on insider k=
nowledge of some star player=E2=80=99s injury or trade demands, and you had=
 some duty to that player to keep that knowledge private,=C2=A0maybe that i=
s  insider trading in sports bets. And of course:Damian Williams, the Unite=
d States Attorney for the Southern District of New York, and Michael J. Dri=
scoll, Assistant Director-in-Charge of the New York Field Office of the Fed=
eral Bureau of Investigation (=E2=80=9CFBI=E2=80=9D), announced [Wednesday]=
 the unsealing of an Indictment charging NATHANIEL CHASTAIN, a former produ=
ct manager at Ozone Networks, Inc. d/b/a OpenSea (=E2=80=9COpenSea=E2=80=9D=
), with wire fraud and money laundering in connection with a scheme to comm=
it insider trading in Non-Fungible Tokens, or =E2=80=9CNFTs,=E2=80=9D by us=
ing confidential information about what NFTs were going to be featured on O=
penSea=E2=80=99s homepage for his personal financial gain. =C2=A0...U.S. At=
torney Damian Williams said: =C2=A0=E2=80=9CNFTs might be new, but this typ=
e of criminal scheme is not. =C2=A0As alleged, Nathaniel Chastain betrayed =
OpenSea by using its confidential business information to make money for hi=
mself. =C2=A0Today=E2=80=99s charges demonstrate the commitment of this Off=
ice to stamping out insider trading =E2=80=93 whether it occurs on the stoc=
k market or the blockchain.=E2=80=9DFBI Assistant Director-in-Charge Michae=
l J. Driscoll said: =C2=A0=E2=80=9CIn this case, as alleged, Chastain launc=
hed an age-old scheme to commit insider trading by using his knowledge of c=
onfidential information to purchase dozens of NFTs in advance of them being=
 featured on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homepage. With the emergence of any new inve=
stment tool, such as blockchain supported non-fungible tokens, there are th=
ose who will exploit vulnerabilities for their own gain. The FBI will conti=
nue to aggressively pursue actors who choose to manipulate the market in th=
is way.=E2=80=9DIt=E2=80=99s a novel approach, but you see their point. NFT=
s don=E2=80=99t have to be securities for insider trading in them to be wir=
e fraud. On the other hand, I guess you can see Chastain=E2=80=99s point? I=
t=C2=A0is=C2=A0a novel approach. Arguably Chastain (allegedly) invented NFT=
 insider trading; how could have he have known it was wire fraud? Anyway he=
re=E2=80=99s the indictment:OpenSea is an NFT marketplace, where users can =
create, sell, and buy NFTs. Beginning in or about May 2021, the top of the =
homepage of OpenSea=E2=80=99s website started displaying featured NFTs. Ope=
nSea changed the featured NFT multiple times per week. Information about wh=
at NFT and was going to be a featured NFT was OpenSea=E2=80=99s confidentia=
l business information because it was not publicly available until the feat=
ured NFT appeared on the OpenSea website homepage. The value of featured NF=
Ts, as well as other NFTs made by the same NFT creator, typically appreciat=
ed once they appeared on the OpenSea homepage due to the increase in public=
ity and resulting demand for the NFT.From in or about May 2021 to in or abo=
ut September 2021, NATHANIEL CHASTAIN, the defendant, was responsible for s=
electing the NFTs that would be featured on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homepage. =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Employees of OpenSea, including NATHANIEL CHASTAIN, the defenda=
nt, had an obligation to maintain the confidentiality of confidential busin=
ess information received in connection with their work for OpenSea, and an =
obligation to refrain from using such information, except for the benefit o=
f OpenSea or to the extent necessary to perform work for OpenSea. =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0Indeed, upon joining OpenSea, Chastain signed a written agreement in =
which he acknowledged these obligations.=C2=A0And some examples:On August 9=
, 2021, CHASTAIN purchased ten of the NFT =E2=80=9CFlipping and spinning=E2=
=80=9D before it was featured on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homepage, and then sold =
them at prices 250% to 300% higher than where they were before the NFT was =
featured..On September 14, 2021, CHASTAIN purchased the NFT =E2=80=9CSpectr=
um of a Ramenfication Theory,=E2=80=9D as well as three other NFTs by the s=
ame creator, shortly before the NFT was featured on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homep=
age. CHASTAIN made over four times the amount of money when he sold =E2=80=
=9CSpectrum of a Ramenfication Theory=E2=80=9D early the next morning.=C2=
=A0I don=E2=80=99t know. You could tell a story about NFTs that is a story =
about art? I guess? Like, this guy really liked =E2=80=9CSpectrum of a Rame=
nfication Theory,=E2=80=9D as art? (You can see it here; it looks like an N=
FT.) He is an art connoisseur-dealer? He was like =E2=80=9Cthis art is beau=
tiful, and I love it, and I will buy it because I love it, and then I will =
feature it on our homepage because it is so beautiful and I want other peop=
le to appreciate its beauty=E2=80=9D? Like he decided what would be feature=
d, why not both buy and feature what he loved? And then flip it immediately=
 for a profit, sure, not a great fact. Also:To conceal his purchase of feat=
ured NFTs before they appeared on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homepage, NATHANIEL CHA=
STAIN, the defendant, used anonymous OpenSea accounts, instead of his publi=
cly-known account in his own name, to make the purchases and sales. He also=
 transferred funds through multiple anonymous Ethereum accounts in order to=
 conceal his involvement in purchasing and selling the featured NFTs.Seems =
bad. But it is weird to put a person in prison for years because he =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0bought some internet cartoons =E2=80=A6=C2=A0before =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0they were =E2=80=A6=C2=A0put on a website? Like on the one hand it certa=
inly seems like insider trading, sure, but on the other hand, does the US g=
overnment have that much interest in protecting the level playing field of =
trading markets in internet cartoons? Were you really defrauded, when you s=
old this guy a copy of =E2=80=9CFlipping and spinning=E2=80=9D at the going=
 price before he featured it on the homepage? When people worry about insid=
er trading in stocks, it is because they think insider trading undermines c=
onfidence in the stock market. I feel like everything that has ever been th=
ought, said or done about NFTs undermines confidence in the NFT market, so =
it=E2=80=99s kind of random to go after this.By the way,  last week I compl=
ained about crypto insider trading scandals that they are never about funda=
mentals[3]:What is relevant is market depth: If you can sell the project=E2=
=80=99s token to more people, then it will be more valuable. In particular,=
 if it is listed on one of the big cryptocurrency exchanges, the price will=
 go up, because more people will buy it, independent of any considerations =
about what the token actually does or whether the project will ultimately s=
ucceed. =E2=80=A6The inside information is always fundamentally=C2=A0about =
the exchange, not=C2=A0about the project. The core inside information is ne=
ver =E2=80=9Cthe fundamental value of this token has increased,=E2=80=9D al=
ways =E2=80=9Cwe can sell this token to more people.=E2=80=9D It is a dispi=
riting sort of insider trading.It is hard to imagine how you=C2=A0could=C2=
=A0trade on fundamental inside information about =E2=80=9CSpectrum of Ramen=
fication Theory,=E2=80=9D or about art generally, so I guess it makes sense=
 that this case is about what got listed on the homepage. But it does mean =
that no one was=C2=A0deceived=C2=A0about the fundamental value of =E2=80=9C=
Spectrum of Ramenfication Theory.=E2=80=9D If you bought it because you tho=
ught it was pretty, and then sold it to this guy because you=E2=80=99d rath=
er have the money, him putting it on OpenSea=E2=80=99s homepage doesn=E2=80=
=99t change the basic nature of the transaction.=C2=A0
