      Melvin
   =20
 =20
There is a sort of minimal form of a hedge fund that goes like this:=09You =
pick stocks that you think will go up, and buy them. And pick stocks that y=
ou think will go down, and short them. And do whatever other trades you thi=
nk will make money. You have some analysts to help you pick the stocks, and=
 some process that you design, and some notions about position sizing and r=
isk management, but it is all pretty informal. At the end of the day, your =
personal instincts about what stocks will go up drive your investing.=09You=
 are good at it: For years on end, the stocks that you buy go up, and the s=
tocks that you short go down. This means that your fund has good returns, a=
nd also that you can charge your clients a large percentage of those return=
s as performance fees, because it is hard to get good returns so the client=
s are happy to pay for them.=09You don=E2=80=99t have a boss: You are the b=
oss, and the clients don=E2=80=99t bother you because you=E2=80=99re making=
 money.=09There are no rules: You are not at a big institution with a deep-=
rooted=C2=A0culture, or at a heavily regulated entity where every action is=
 scrutinized and lawyered; you=E2=80=99re just a person in a room picking s=
ome stocks however you want.=09You work when and where you want: You need a=
 computer and a phone, but otherwise it doesn=E2=80=99t much matter if you =
come into the office, and if you want to spend the summer at the beach that=
=E2=80=99s fine.=09You buy a lot of houses, yachts, sports teams, etc.This =
is obviously not the=C2=A0only form that hedge funds take; nobody would say=
 =E2=80=9Cthere are no rules=E2=80=9D about, like, Bridgewater. The hedge-f=
und industry is increasingly institutionalized, and big hedge-fund firms lo=
ok a lot like big heavily regulated financial institutions. But this remain=
s a=C2=A0possible=C2=A0form. If you are just really good at knowing which s=
tocks will go up, people will give you money and pay you a lot to manage it=
 and leave you alone.That seems nice? I mean, I feel like a lot of people w=
ould like those basic job parameters? Not everyone is good at picking the s=
tocks, or at raising the money from outside investors to buy the stocks, bu=
t if you are it seems like a good job. You get to work from the beach, own =
sports teams, various nice things.Then if you run into trouble and the stoc=
ks you buy go down (and the stocks you short go up), your clients will star=
t complaining. Perhaps they will want you to stop managing their money, whi=
ch is sad for you; you can=E2=80=99t keep charging them large fees. Alterna=
tively, they will want you to=C2=A0keep=C2=A0managing their money, to make =
up for the money you lost (and justify the high fees that they already paid=
 you). But they will want you to do it in a different, less personally sati=
sfying way. Instead of just trusting your gut, they will want you to impose=
 disciplined risk management procedures to reduce the odds of losing more m=
oney. Instead of working from the beach, they will want you to sit at your =
desk, to make sure you=E2=80=99re working for them and also as penance for =
losing their money. You lost so much money, why are you at the beach?Here i=
s a  Bloomberg News story about Gabe Plotkin=E2=80=99s Melvin Capital Manag=
ement, which really seems to have operated on the old-school minimal-form h=
edge-fund model. =E2=80=9CMelvin was the envy of the hedge fund world for a=
 half-decade, posting annualized returns of 30% that let it charge some of =
the most expensive performance fees in the industry, sometimes up to 30%,=
=E2=80=9D before losing 57% in the last year and a half and shutting down l=
ast month:Betting on a star investor who drives their own firm can make for=
 a wild ride. Melvin, like many single-manager funds its size, lacked many =
of the trappings of bigger institutional money managers, such as an operati=
ng committee to vote on key decisions. Instead Plotkin, 43, gathered advice=
 and information, discussed his thinking with a tight circle, and once he d=
eveloped a view, acted swiftly -- sometimes with contrarian moves that caug=
ht clients and staff off guard.=C2=A0Such stealth, speed and conviction can=
 generate a fortune in markets. But for running a business, it makes life u=
npredictable.As returns swung over the past year, some investors hoped Plot=
kin would stabilize Melvin by beefing up risk management, and even broached=
 the topic to no avail. When investors later submitted a wide range of sugg=
estions for more dramatic overhauls, Plotkin listened but ultimately didn=
=E2=80=99t follow the advice.Their suggestions were things like =E2=80=9Chi=
re risk managers=E2=80=9D:[Outside investor] Point72 urged Plotkin to bolst=
er his risk team by making additional hires and installing a senior risk of=
ficer.And =E2=80=9Ccome back to the office=E2=80=9D:To [head of outside inv=
estor Citadel=C2=A0Ken] Griffin=E2=80=99s dismay, Melvin was slow in puttin=
g a stop to work-from-home flexibility allowed during the pandemic. The bil=
lionaire backer, a staunch advocate of returning to offices, threatened to =
pull money if Plotkin didn=E2=80=99t summon his team back full-time. Yet Pl=
otkin continued to work mainly out of his waterfront Miami house and a near=
by Melvin outpost. Many traders, scattered around the country, came into of=
fices only a couple days a week. Citadel began redeeming its cash around mi=
d-2021.Meanwhile Plotkin had his own ideas, like =E2=80=9Ckeep paying perfo=
rmance fees despite our losses=E2=80=9D:In April, he floated an unusual pla=
n. The firm would attempt a reboot -- shrinking the fund and resuming perfo=
rmance fees even though it was still in the red. =E2=80=9CNavigating volati=
le markets had become more difficult than in the past,=E2=80=9D Plotkin wro=
te in a letter to investors. Some employees were stunned. The proposal was =
lampooned on Wall Street.Plotkin reversed course. He apologized to investor=
s in a letter, which circulated on social media. He then had the firm meet =
with customers to weigh alternatives. He was exhausted.Yes, look, this all =
sounds less fun than his previous career of collecting hundreds of millions=
 of dollars of performance fees, investing however he wanted, and buying =
=E2=80=9Ca stake in the National Basketball Association=E2=80=99s Charlotte=
 Hornets.=E2=80=9D So he shut down the fund to, I hope, spend more time wit=
h his sports team and beach house.=C2=A0I feel like people want to make thi=
s more complicated than it is?In recent days, executives at Blackstone Inc.=
=E2=80=99s hedge fund arm, which oversees client money in Melvin, have been=
 fielding investor calls about lessons learned and what could be done to av=
ert such a situation in the future, people familiar with the matter said.Ye=
ah the lesson is =E2=80=9Cif you give a lot of money to a hedge fund manage=
r who gets great returns with minimal structure, try to get your money back=
 before he starts losing money=E2=80=9D? Like, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t=C2=A0=
invest with a guy who is going to make 30% a year for five years=E2=80=9D s=
eems like a tough lesson to learn, while =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t invest with=
 a guy who is going to lose 57% over a year and a half=E2=80=9D seems like =
a tough one to implement.=C2=A0
