   =20
      Archegos
   =20
 =20
Still elsewhere in hedge-fund-shaped entities that have not had a great 202=
1 and 2022, we have  talked before about the strange federal criminal case =
against Archegos Capital Management, the exploded family office of former T=
iger Management investor Bill Hwang. The case has two elements, and they ar=
e both strange:=09Hwang and his employees allegedly did market manipulation=
, by making huge concentrated levered bets on a handful of stocks, which pu=
shed those stocks up. This is a weird sort of market manipulation: Yes, buy=
ing a lot of stock will push the price up, but it is not illegal to buy a l=
ot of stock. Ordinarily market manipulation involves pushing the price up i=
n one market to make a profit elsewhere, or at the very least sending bad e=
mails and chats saying =E2=80=9Clol I am buying this stock to push the pric=
e up.=E2=80=9D Here there is none of that. Archegos just bought a lot of st=
ock at increasing prices, and then lost all its money when the prices went =
back down. What was the manipulative plan here?=09Hwang and his employees a=
llegedly lied to Archegos=E2=80=99s banks about how big and concentrated an=
d levered their positions were: Archegos had a bunch of banks, and each ban=
k saw only a portion of Archegos=E2=80=99s portfolio, and each bank thought=
 =E2=80=9Cwell, sure Archegos=E2=80=99s trades with us are big and concentr=
ated and levered, but I=E2=80=99m sure its positions with=C2=A0other=C2=A0b=
anks are nice and liquid and diversified.=E2=80=9D This is weird because Cr=
edit Suisse Group AG, the bank that  lost the most money on Archegos, publi=
shed a blunt post-mortem that   makes it very clear that Credit Suisse knew=
 all about how big and concentrated and levered Archegos=E2=80=99s overall =
portfolio was. Credit Suisse, at least, was not=C2=A0deceived=C2=A0by Arche=
gos; Credit Suisse saw the problems and kept financing Archegos anyway for =
commercial reasons. Perhaps all of Archegos=E2=80=99s=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks=
 were deceived, but, again, Credit Suisse is the one that did the worst her=
e, and it was not.Here is an  update from the criminal case:Archegos Capita=
l Management, Hwang=E2=80=99s family office, and the banks were like =E2=80=
=9CShaq and LeBron,=E2=80=9D said Mary Mulligan, who represents [former chi=
ef financial officer Patrick] Halligan, at a pretrial hearing Wednesday in =
federal court in Manhattan. In the NBA, she said, everybody plays with =E2=
=80=9Csharp elbows.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThese banks are sophisticated an=
d have outside counsel,=E2=80=9D she told US District Judge Alvin Hellerste=
in. When it came to interactions between Halligan and the banks, she said, =
=E2=80=9Ceverybody knows the rules of the game.=E2=80=9DHwang=E2=80=99s law=
yer Lawrence Lustberg said the government=E2=80=99s case featured an =E2=80=
=9Cunprecedented, extraordinary, never-before-seen theory of stock manipula=
tion.=E2=80=9D Lustberg said manipulation depends on someone sending false =
signals to the market and that there were no such signals from Hwang.=C2=A0=
I feel like the old =E2=80=9Cwell everyone knew we were lying to them=E2=80=
=9D defense does not always play well, but overall I sympathize with this? =
The banks do not seem to have been particularly deceived by Archegos, and i=
f it=C2=A0was=C2=A0manipulating stock prices it wasn=E2=80=99t doing so in =
a way designed to, uh, make money? Obviously there is something=C2=A0wrong=
=C2=A0with what happened at Archegos, but I am not sure that prosecutors ha=
ve yet found the appropriate=C2=A0crime.
