      Game show
   =20
 =20
Sure:The Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s Office of Investor Ed=
ucation and Advocacy [Wednesday] unveiled a game show-themed public service=
 campaign to help investors make informed investment decisions and avoid fr=
aud. Recognizing that sometimes investing may look and feel like a game, th=
e campaign titled =E2=80=9CInvestomania=E2=80=9D reminds investors to do th=
eir due diligence when making investment decisions.One of the goals of the =
Investomania campaign, which features a 30-second TV spot, 15-second inform=
ational videos on crypto assets, margin calls, and guaranteed returns, and =
interactive quizzes, is to reach existing, new, and future investors of all=
 ages. The campaign encourages investors to research investments and get in=
formation from trustworthy sources to understand the risks before investing=
. The campaign also reminds investors to take advantage of the free financi=
al planning tools and information on Investor.gov, the SEC=E2=80=99s resour=
ce for investor education.Here=E2=80=99s the 30-second TV game show, which =
shows a guy saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll take meme stocks! Invest!=E2=80=9D=
 and then hitting a button. And then his money falls through a trap door=C2=
=A0and he gets hit in the face with a pie. I love that the SEC really wante=
d to stop people from investing in the great 2021 meme-stock craze, and it =
couldn=E2=80=99t quite, like, ban meme stocks, so it came up with passive-a=
ggressive approaches like requiring meme-stock companies=C2=A0to say =E2=80=
=9Cthis is all dumb=E2=80=9D  in their prospectuses if they wanted to raise=
 money, or putting out a commercial making fun of meme stocks a year and a =
half later. There=E2=80=99s also a 15-second spot making fun of actors shil=
ling for crypto.
