 under section 12=C2=A0of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.=E2=80=9D The=
 securities-law statute is Section 10(b) of the Securities Exchange Act of =
1934, 15 USC 78j(b),=C2=A0making it unlawful =E2=80=9Cto use or employ, in =
connection with the purchase or sale of any security registered on a nation=
al securities exchange or any security not so registered =E2=80=A6 any mani=
pulative or deceptive device or contrivance in contravention of such rules =
and regulations as the Commission may prescribe as necessary or appropriate=
 in the public interest or for the protection of investors.=E2=80=9D And th=
e most important of those rules is Rule 10b-5, making it illegal =E2=80=9Ct=
o employ any device, scheme, or artifice to defraud,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ct=
o engage in any act, practice, or course of business which operates or woul=
d operate as a fraud or deceit upon any person, in connection with the purc=
hase or sale of any security.=E2=80=9D[2] Or a television, radio, etc. This=
 is 18 USC 1343.[3] I got one email from a reader pointing out, as a counte=
rexample, a mergers-and-acquisitions-based, fundamentals-ish alleged NFT in=
sider trade. =E2=80=9CBored Apes Yacht Club maker Yuga Labs announced [in M=
arch] that they have acquired the rights to the CryptoPunks and Meebits NFT=
 collections from creator Larva Labs,=E2=80=9D and you could have had a vie=
w like =E2=80=9CYuga Labs is really good at making NFT collections valuable=
, so this will increase the value of those collections.=E2=80=9D And there =
were allegations that people connected to the deal bought Meebits before it=
 was announced.
