<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Melvin</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a sort of minimal form of a h=
edge fund that goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pa=
dding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You=
 pick stocks that you think will go up, and buy them. And pick stocks that =
you think will go down, and short them. And do whatever other trades you th=
ink will make money. You have some analysts to help you pick the stocks, an=
d some process that you design, and some notions about position sizing and =
risk management, but it is all pretty informal. At the end of the day, your=
 personal instincts about what stocks will go up drive your investing.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are good at it: For years on end, =
the stocks that you buy go up, and the stocks that you short go down. This =
means that your fund has good returns, and also that you can charge your cl=
ients a large percentage of those returns as performance fees, because it i=
s hard to get good returns so the clients are happy to pay for them.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t have a boss: You are=
 the boss, and the clients don=E2=80=99t bother you because you=E2=80=99re =
making money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are no rules: =
You are not at a big institution with a deep-rooted=C2=A0culture, or at a h=
eavily regulated entity where every action is scrutinized and lawyered; you=
=E2=80=99re just a person in a room picking some stocks however you want.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You work when and where you want: Y=
ou need a computer and a phone, but otherwise it doesn=E2=80=99t much matte=
r if you come into the office, and if you want to spend the summer at the b=
each that=E2=80=99s fine.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy =
a lot of houses, yachts, sports teams, etc.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">This is obviously not the=C2=A0<em>only </em>form that hedge funds t=
ake; nobody would say =E2=80=9Cthere are no rules=E2=80=9D about, like, Bri=
dgewater. The hedge-fund industry is increasingly institutionalized, and bi=
g hedge-fund firms look a lot like big heavily regulated financial institut=
ions. But this remains a=C2=A0<em>possible=C2=A0</em>form. If you are just =
really good at knowing which stocks will go up, people will give you money =
and pay you a lot to manage it and leave you alone.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">That seems nice? I mean, I feel like a lot of people would like th=
ose basic job parameters? Not everyone is good at picking the stocks, or at=
 raising the money from outside investors to buy the stocks, but if you are=
 it seems like a good job. You get to work from the beach, own sports teams=
, various nice things.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then if you run into=
 trouble and the stocks you buy go down (and the stocks you short go up), y=
our clients will start complaining. Perhaps they will want you to stop mana=
ging their money, which is sad for you; you can=E2=80=99t keep charging the=
m large fees. Alternatively, they will want you to=C2=A0<em>keep=C2=A0</em>=
managing their money, to make up for the money you lost (and justify the hi=
gh fees that they already paid you). But they will want you to do it in a d=
ifferent, less personally satisfying way. Instead of just trusting your gut=
, they will want you to impose disciplined risk management procedures to re=
duce the odds of losing more money. Instead of working from the beach, they=
 will want you to sit at your desk, to make sure you=E2=80=99re working for=
 them and also as penance for losing their money. You lost so much money, w=
hy are you at the beach?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27923003.286612/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDIvcGxvdGtpbi1zLXdp=
bGQtcmlkZS1yZXZlYWxzLXBlcmlscy1vZi1iZXR0aW5nLW9uLWEtc3Rhci10cmFkZXI_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDYwMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBb4f2da69" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg News story</a> about Gabe Plotkin=E2=
=80=99s Melvin Capital Management, which really seems to have operated on t=
he old-school minimal-form hedge-fund model. =E2=80=9CMelvin was the envy o=
f the hedge fund world for a half-decade, posting annualized returns of 30%=
 that let it charge some of the most expensive performance fees in the indu=
stry, sometimes up to 30%,=E2=80=9D before losing 57% in the last year and =
a half and shutting down last month:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Betting on a star investor who drives their own firm can make for a w=
ild ride. Melvin, like many single-manager funds its size, lacked many of t=
he trappings of bigger institutional money managers, such as an operating c=
ommittee to vote on key decisions. Instead Plotkin, 43, gathered advice and=
 information, discussed his thinking with a tight circle, and once he devel=
oped a view, acted swiftly -- sometimes with contrarian moves that caught c=
lients and staff off guard.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Such stea=
lth, speed and conviction can generate a fortune in markets. But for runnin=
g a business, it makes life unpredictable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
As returns swung over the past year, some investors hoped Plotkin would sta=
bilize Melvin by beefing up risk management, and even broached the topic to=
 no avail. When investors later submitted a wide range of suggestions for m=
ore dramatic overhauls, Plotkin listened but ultimately didn=E2=80=99t foll=
ow the advice.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Their suggestio=
ns were things like =E2=80=9Chire risk managers=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Outside investor] Point72 urged Plotkin to bols=
ter his risk team by making additional hires and installing a senior risk o=
fficer.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And =E2=80=9Ccome back=
 to the office=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To [he=
ad of outside investor Citadel=C2=A0Ken] Griffin=E2=80=99s dismay, Melvin w=
as slow in putting a stop to work-from-home flexibility allowed during the =
pandemic. The billionaire backer, a staunch advocate of returning to office=
s, threatened to pull money if Plotkin didn=E2=80=99t summon his team back =
full-time. Yet Plotkin continued to work mainly out of his waterfront Miami=
 house and a nearby Melvin outpost. Many traders, scattered around the coun=
try, came into offices only a couple days a week. Citadel began redeeming i=
ts cash around mid-2021.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanw=
hile Plotkin had his own ideas, like =E2=80=9Ckeep paying performance fees =
despite our losses=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In=
 April, he floated an unusual plan. The firm would attempt a reboot -- shri=
nking the fund and resuming performance fees even though it was still in th=
e red. =E2=80=9CNavigating volatile markets had become more difficult than =
in the past,=E2=80=9D Plotkin wrote in a letter to investors. Some employee=
s were stunned. The proposal was lampooned on Wall Street.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Plotkin reversed course. He apologized to investors in a le=
tter, which circulated on social media. He then had the firm meet with cust=
omers to weigh alternatives. He was exhausted.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Yes, look, this all sounds less fun than his previous care=
er of collecting hundreds of millions of dollars of performance fees, inves=
ting however he wanted, and buying =E2=80=9Ca stake in the National Basketb=
all Association=E2=80=99s Charlotte Hornets.=E2=80=9D So he shut down the f=
und to, I hope, spend more time with his sports team and beach house.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like people want to make this more =
complicated than it is?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In rece=
nt days, executives at Blackstone Inc.=E2=80=99s hedge fund arm, which over=
sees client money in Melvin, have been fielding investor calls about lesson=
s learned and what could be done to avert such a situation in the future, p=
eople familiar with the matter said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Yeah the lesson is =E2=80=9Cif you give a lot of money to a hedge fu=
nd manager who gets great returns with minimal structure, try to get your m=
oney back before he starts losing money=E2=80=9D? Like, =E2=80=9C<em>don=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0</em>invest with a guy who is going to make 30% a year for fiv=
e years=E2=80=9D seems like a tough lesson to learn, while =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=
=80=99t invest with a guy who is going to lose 57% over a year and a half=
=E2=80=9D seems like a tough one to implement.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"liv=
eintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"=
center">
